  "prompt": "What is the future of TV like in Asia? Will there be a new Netflix/Hulu here or will Netflix/Hulu extend their reach here?",
  "response": "The future of TV in Asia is complex and varies by country, but here are some key trends:\n\n1. Streaming Services:\n- Netflix and Amazon Prime are already present in many Asian markets\n- Local streaming platforms are growing strongly, such as:\n  - iQiyi (China)\n- Viu (Hong Kong-based, popular in Southeast Asia)\n- Hotstar (India)\n- WeTV (China)\n\n2. Market Dynamics:\n- Each country has unique preferences and local content\n- Local platforms often have advantages in understanding regional tastes\n- Regulatory environments differ significantly between countries\n\n3. Potential Developments:\n- More localized content production\n- Increasing mobile-first viewing\n- Bundling with telecom services\n- Growth of ad-supported models\n\n4. Country-Specific Variations:\n- China has strict regulations, limiting foreign streaming services\n- India has a massive, rapidly growing digital market\n- Southeast Asian countries show increasing digital consumption\n\n5. Competition:\n- Global players like Netflix are investing heavily in local content\n- Local platforms are becoming more sophisticated\n- Potential for mergers and acquisitions\n\nOverall, the market is dynamic, with both global and local players competing and adapting to regional preferences.",
